//
// ✅ REALISTIC LIFT PHYSICS SETUP:
// =================================
//
// 1. HEATSINK (Y = 0-8μm):
//    - Solid substrate (alpha.metal = 1)
//    - Acts as thermal boundary and mechanical constraint
//    - Provides heat sink effect
//    - Prevents downward expansion of metal
//
// 2. METAL FILM (Y = 8-8.0714μm):
//    - Pure titanium donor material
//    - 71.4 nm thickness
//    - Will be heated by laser and undergo phase change
//    - Source of ejected droplets
//
// 3. AIR GAP (Y = 8.0714-30μm):
//    - Space for droplet ejection and flight
//    - Collection zone for LIFT process
//    - Allows visualization of ejection dynamics
//
// 4. LASER FOCUS:
//    - Positioned at substrate/metal interface (Y ≈ 8μm)
//    - Creates localized heating for LIFT
//    - Substrate constrains expansion downward
//    - Forces material ejection upward into air gap
//
// This setup captures the essential LIFT physics:
// - Substrate backing and thermal effects
// - Thin donor film for efficient heating
// - Adequate air space for ejection dynamics
// - Realistic geometry and material distribution
//
// Expected LIFT sequence:
// 1. Laser heats metal at substrate interface
// 2. Rapid temperature rise and phase change
// 3. Pressure buildup constrained by substrate
// 4. Explosive ejection into air gap
// 5. Droplet formation and flight
